postcontent: Seller Stock #: LG51121 Here is the original AK-47 trainer introduced during the Reagan Era, and wildly popular during the Bush Sr / Clinton Ban Years. This AK-22 is manufactured by Armscor of the Philippines, the company that brings us their excellent 1911 pistols that perform so very well. Importer and warrantor is Armscor Precision of Pahrump, Nevada. Construction is steel barrel, bolt, trigger guard, gas tube, sight post and leaf, screws, lever, and internal parts built into an alloy Action with alloy sight body, tube hardware, and trigger. Buttstock, forend, cover, and pistol grip are oil finish Filipino hardwood. Despite the imitation gas tube, type is blowback semi-auto, and it is a direct descendant of the Remington 550-1 rifles that are still in service after 60 years. Action is not at all Kalashnikov, so this rifle is not proscripted by anti-AK State and Local laws. Sights are correct elevation adjustable square notch rear and hooded blade front. Sling is 1 1/2 inch black military style, and it attaches easily to the permanent swivels. We have sold substantial numbers of this brand rifle with good results since the 1970s, when the 550-1 phased out and the Filipino manufacturers filled the gap with a good quality economically priced rifle marketed under the Squibman and K-Mart brands, then Armscor. This wonderful Colt is one of approximately 1000 pistols that Colt manufactured during the transition period preceding the introduction of the Series 70 1911s. title: For Sale:  Walther G22 Bullpup .22 LR rifle w/ laser, bipod
location: Cary, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
For sale is a Walther G22 rifle in excellent condition, with the laser attachment, UTG bipod, original hard case, and two original 10-round magazines.  I am the original and sole owner.

The rifle is missing its original charging handle, and I have replaced it with one that I mocked up, as you can see in the photos.  The replacement functions exactly like the original -- there's no play in it and it's comfortable to use.  I also have additional long machine screws to fit the bolt so you can make your own version with plastic or metal standoffs if you want.

Condition:
The bore is in immaculate condition, but I was unable to get a good photo of it.  There is a small patch of minor pitting on the top of the barrel where the metal is first exposed.  It's very difficult to see in person.  There's some finish wear on the barrel where it meets the red sliding safety indicators, and some wear on the ends of the disassembly pins.  Other than that, there's not really any wear or cosmetic problems to speak of.

The case (not pictured) is in good, functional condition.  It shows plenty of use, including some damage to the foam inside, but is fully functional.  I actually have been using it for lots of other smaller guns when I am not taking the G22 to the range.

History:
The gun has around 3000 rounds through it.  Bulk ammo works well.  I have had good luck with many different types of .22 LR.  Early on, it didn't like Remington Golden Bullet, but either it "broke in" or Remington changed their ammo, because it seems to run fine with it now.  Several months after buying the gun, I sent it off for repair because the trigger bar (connecting the trigger back to the sear) was able to bend too much, causing a "squishy" trigger.  Smith and Wesson replaced the part and sent it back much better.  I haven't had a problem with it since.

Overall, the gun handles and operates very well and is amazingly accurate for a semi-auto.  The main negative is that it's a pain to take apart to clean (similar to a Ruger Mark 2 or 3 in annoyance level).  The good news is that a bore snake and an external wipe-down is really all that's necessary 90% of the time.  The gun tolerates lots of internal dirt and fouling.

I'd recommend the gun for any bullpup enthusiasts or for rimfire action competitions, due to its handling characteristics and super-short overall length.

Asking $325 for everything.  Other offers considered, but I'm in no hurry to sell the rifle, so don't waste your time with a low-ball offer.  No trades.

Pick up in Cary is GREATLY preferred.  If you need it shipped, you'll need to add the cost of shipping and the outgoing FFL fee, which I would estimate at $55 total.  I'll also need a picture or scan of your driver's license, regardless of delivery method.

Thanks for looking!
